   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                           Wonder</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>The Wonder: A Woman Keeps a Secret</title>; A
                              Comedy, In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna"
                                 >Mrs. Centlivre</ref>. As Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XI. <hi rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Busy Body</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Wonder</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Bold
                              Stroke for a Wife</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>George
                              Barnwell</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Fatal
                              Curiosity</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and
                        Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged
                        at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref>
                        on April 27<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1714. Laura DeWitt and Mary A.
                        Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                           Archive</hi>.</note></title>
                  <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </bibl>
            </head>
            <p><ref target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Mrs. Centlivre</ref>, who wrote this
               comedy, and of whose life a short account has been given in the remarks upon her play
               of "<title>The Busy Body</title>," ranks in the first class of our comic dramatists:
               for though she does not possess the repartee of <ref
                  target="people.html#CongreveWilliam">Congreve</ref> or <ref
                  target="people.html#WycherleyWilliam">Wycherly</ref>, and her dialogue, in
               general, is not equal even to <ref target="people.html#FarquharGeorge"
               >Farquhar</ref>'s, yet she discovers such happy invention in her plots, incidents,
               and characters; such skill in conducting the intrigues of a comedy; such art in
               exciting the curiosity, the anxiety, or the mirth of her auditors, that she foils
               both the scholar and the wit when the comparison is limited to theatrical effect.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#CongreveWilliam">Congreve</ref> abandoned his occupation as
               a dramatist in violent anger, because his "<title>Way of the World</title>" appeared,
               and was totally neglected, at the very time that a comedy by <ref
                  target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Mrs. Centlivre</ref> was brought forth, and
               attracted, for thirteen nights successively, a crowded theatre.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> draws the notion of <ref
                     target="people.html#CongreveWilliam">William Congreve</ref>'s jealousy of <ref
                     target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Centlivre</ref> from <ref
                     target="people.html#BakerDavid">David Erskine Baker</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Companion to the Play-House</title></hi> (1764,
                  volume II, p. unnumbered). <ref target="people.html#CongreveWilliam"
                     >Congreve</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Way of the World</title></hi>
                  and <ref target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Centlivre</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Perjur'd Husband: or, The Adventures of
                        Venice</title></hi> both premiered in 1700&#8212;both plays were considered
                  failures, with <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Perjur'd Husband</title></hi>
                  running only five nights and <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Way of the
                        World</title></hi> running for seven. <ref
                     target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Centlivre</ref>'s 1709 play <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Busy Body</title></hi> ran for thirteen
                  nights.</note></p>

            <p>Merely as writers, the author of "<title>The Way of the World</title>," and the
               authoress of "<title>The Wonder</title>," hold distinct places among the literati;
               but as plays are productions that depend on action, and require<fw type="sig">
                  <hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi>
               </fw><pb n="4"/> talents of a nature, in which writing has, perhaps, the smallest
               share, <ref target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Mrs. Centlivre</ref> has, from the
               time she commenced dramatic author to the present day, through all the vicissitudes
               of taste which have, in that period, intervened, still been more attractive on the
               stage than the great poet whom her success offended.</p>

            <p>This comedy is by far her best work. In excellence of fable, strength of character,
               and intricacy of occurrence, it forms one of the most entertaining exhibitions the
               theatre can boast.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> thought Don Felix<note>The plot
                  of <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Wonder</title></hi> revolves around two
                  pairs of lovers, Don Felix and Violante, and Colonel Britton and Isabella. Don
                  Felix is the son of a Portuguese nobleman, Don Lopez, and the brother of
                  Isabella.</note> worthy his most powerful exertions, in describing the passion of
               jealousy; and this character was upon the list with the favourite parts he
               performed.</p>

            <p>Though the scene is in Spain,<note>This comedy is set in Lisbon, the capital of
                  Portugal.</note> and all the manners particularly adapted to that country,
                  "<title>The Wonder</title>" shows the various passions and sensations of all
               mankind. The very servants are objects of attention and curiosity; nor is the humour
               they produce ever so degraded and ludicrous, as to diminish the effect of the more
               refined comedy of the higher personages.<note>Much of the play's comedy relies on the
                  main characters' footservants and maids: Gibby, Lissardo, Inis, and
               Flora.</note></p>

            <p>Most comic writers of the present time accomplish the tedious labour of a five act
               drama by having recourse, alternately, to sentiment and drollery: here a long play is
               sustained with excursions to either; and yet, its consistency in adhering to one
               fixed point of entertainment, never creates satiety, nor shows a languor of invention
               in the author, which for a moment leaves the expectation of the auditor<pb n="5"/>
               unemployed, or leaves that expectation in one single instance disappointed.</p>

            <p>Violante, in keeping a secret, is a heroine of the very first quality. To kill a
               tyrant, or to kill herself, is the common furious deed of a common stage virago: but
               for a female to hold her tongue, is a cool act of deliberate fortitude; and nothing
               but the improbability of the occurrence, can lessen its value with the most severe
                  critic.<note>Isabella is saved by Colonel Britton when she jumps out of a window
                  trying to escape her imminent arranged marriage. Colonel Britton brings Isabella
                  to Violante's house, and Violante keeps the secret of Isabella's presence
                  throughout the play despite it endangering her relationship with Don
               Felix.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Mrs. Centlivre</ref> has somewhere said,
               that&#8212;"The muses, like most females, are least liberal to their own
                  sex."<note>From the dedication "To His Grace <ref
                     target="people.html#WhartonPhilip">Philip, Duke and Marquis of Wharton</ref>,
                  &amp;c." preceding the 1718 publication of <ref
                     target="people.html#CentlivreSusanna">Centlivre</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>A Bold Stroke for a Wife</title></hi> (p.
                  iv).</note> She was ungrateful if she did not acknowledge her obligations to them
               in the composition of this work; for they presided, with no niggardly influence, over
               the whole production.</p>
            <fw type="sig">
               <hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi>
            </fw>
         </div>
      </body>
